        {
            "id": "51f9ee97e21f05cb756949fd360d2f42882ab203",
            "author": {
                "_account_id": 6159,
                "name": "Flavio Percoco",
                "display_name": "flaper87",
                "email": "fpercoco@redhat.com",
                "username": "flaper87"
            },
            "real_author": {
                "_account_id": 6159,
                "name": "Flavio Percoco",
                "display_name": "flaper87",
                "email": "fpercoco@redhat.com",
                "username": "flaper87"
            },
            "date": "2016-05-19 11:44:28.000000000",
            "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nExpanding a bit more on the indexing topic. I've been wondering whether we really need to index `lite-specs`. I mean, these are small changes that require some discussion - hence the required extra tests and release notes - but we don't really need to list them under the \"specs\" things. Actually, I'd as far as saying we should not use the `specs` link as the reference for implemented \"things\" but rather use the release notes link[0].\n\n\nThere we should have release notes for bugs, lite-specs *and* specs. The latter can point to the actual spec but the link used to show progress should be the release notes one rather than the specs one.\n\nDoes the above sound completely crazy?\n\n[0] http://docs.openstack.org/releasenotes/glance/mitaka.html",
            "accounts_in_message": [],
            "_revision_number": 1
        },
